Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt:
10:15 AM Prosecuting attorney Rick C Spoentgen in court for the State of Wisconsin.  Defendant Jessica J D Schwichtenberg in court.  Court states case and appearances.  Court advises DE of right to counsel.  DE states she applied for a PD but was told she didn't qualify.  DE doesn't wish to proceed w/o counsel.  Court questions DE on what she has done to try and get counsel.  DE notes her financial status.  Court will have DE fill out petition for court-appointed counsel.  State requests time limits be addressed so the officer can be released.  Court won't address that yet.  Recess at 10:18 a.m. for DE to fill out paperwork.  Back on the record at 10:50 a.m.  Court questions DE on her petition for court-appointed counsel.  Court swears DE in and has her testify as to the documents.  Court finds DE conditionally indigent and appoints Atty Blake Duren (608) 416-9066.  To reimburse COC's office $75/month beginning on 10/1/22 and then by the first of each month thereafter.  DE asks for another attorney as Atty Duren represented her in the past.  Court denies that request.  Court resets PH noting she will waive the time limits.
